    "description": "<span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/ffa6008c09de2d1c430177f524b074f8.avif?t=1678447861\" width=604 height=328 /></span><br>Database: Gates represents more focused analyses.<br><br>This is the foundation for more detailed content, some of which is hinted in the base application, &quot;Integument.&quot;<br><br>An interesting hada called, Gates is the data set that you'll be working with. Below is a partial list of its contents.<br><span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/f5120d079cec3ef132a1e71e5f0b7f33.avif?t=1678447861\" width=599 height=317 /></span><br><ul class=\"bb_ul\"><li>Anatomical Diagrams</li></ul>Based on spatial reconstructions several hada are presented with labeled anatomy<br><span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/c2b70e75d282e1db3b6f03fa149c1ab9.avif?t=1678447861\" width=470 height=329 /></span><br><span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/ee5cd61b930171c8363e209edd584669.avif?t=1678447861\" width=455 height=326 /></span><br><br><ul class=\"bb_ul\"><li>Glossary of terms</li></ul>A list of terms used in the anatomical diagrams with brief definitions.<br><br><ul class=\"bb_ul\"><li>Ultrastructural analysis</li></ul><span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/db8bea42d933a1f7e0efa2a9b367cf2c.avif?t=1678447861\" width=606 height=329 /></span><br>Reveals fine surface details of the subject sample (waveguide scatter filter).<br><span class=\"bb_img_ctn\"><img class=\"bb_img\" src=\"https://shared.akamai.steamstatic.com/store_item_assets/steam/apps/2139080/extras/ff4ea9969bbdbea16862217b6b1943d7.avif?t=1678447861\" width=589 height=329 /></span><br><br><ul class=\"bb_ul\"><li>Several soundtracks</li></ul>Quantum computers, in their downtime, often convert lab notes into music in an attempt to quantify and understand human abstraction. The music serves to capture the feeling, intent, and observation of the lab work at the time of input. This can trigger memory or inspire the original author. Note, the original format is encoded in the music for classical data access.",
